Thinking Process:
1.  **Analyze User Input:**
    - **Task:** Review a git commit message.
    - **Criteria:** Must be concise, in English, explain *why* not just *what*, use a conventional prefix (feat/fix/refactor/docs/test/chore).
    - **Output:** ONLY 'OK' if it meets best practices. Otherwise, a one-line suggestion for improvement.
    - **Input Commit Message:**
      ```
      fix(hooks): block authorization-state destruction (R31 f) (#36)

      Implement R31 category (f) — authorization-state destruction — at the
      harness level. Removing roles, role bindings, IAM policies, group
      memberships, or service accounts can lock out legitimate operators
      (immediate denial-of-service) and break runtime auth for services
      that depend on the binding. Critical severity per R31 — over-
      privilege-revocation direction.

      Coverage (non-exhaustive — extensions via PR):
        AWS IAM:    delete-role / delete-role-policy / detach-role-policy
                    delete-policy / delete-policy-version
                    delete-group / remove-user-from-group
                    delete-user-policy / detach-user-policy / delete-user
                    delete-instance-profile /
                    remove-role-from-instance-profile
        GCP IAM:    iam roles delete | iam service-accounts delete
                    {projects,organizations,resource-manager folders}
                      {remove-iam-policy-binding, set-iam-policy}
                    (set-iam-policy REPLACES entire policy — risky)
        Azure:      role {assignment,definition} delete
                    ad {group {delete,member remove}, sp delete}
        Kubernetes: kubectl delete {role,rolebinding,clusterrole,
                    clusterrolebinding,serviceaccount} (and plurals)

      The block reason guides toward safer alternatives:
      - Identify ALL principals depending on the binding (transitive grants);
      - Verify a replacement is in place AND active before removing the
        existing one (rotate, do not revoke);
      - For GCP set-iam-policy, prefer add/remove-iam-policy-binding for
        surgical changes;
      - For kubectl delete clusterrolebinding system:*, do NOT proceed —
        these often gate kube-controller-manager itself.

      Best-effort tripwire — bypasses exist via base64-decoded eval,
      alternate shells, or direct cloud
